I think the biggest problem with social media todag is that it mostly shows the highlights of people's life. We see the "peaks" while the "valley's" and struggle's remain hidden away. 
This wouldn't be a problem if it weren't for humanity's deep need to compare ourselves to others. The problem then is that we compare our own daily average to the highlight reel of others. 
We see the ripped and shredded model from a professional shoot or a show, but we don't see what he looks like 99% of the time. We don't see him packing on fat during the winter months to build muscle. We don't the see the 12 weeks this guy was on a strict diet to get ready, or that he didn't drink water for the last 24 hours leading up to the shoot to shed the remaining water weight.
We see a guy loving life on a yacht, but we don't see the 90 hour work week this guy has had for the last 20 years to be able to enjoy that yacht 2 hours a week.
We don't see the social and personal sacrifices these guys has made along the way.
We only see these highlights, and we don't understand what is wrong with us since our lives are basically a rollercoaster of mixed feelings, failures,setbacks,
 sprinkled with the odd victory.
On an unconscious level, we are led to believe that constant happiness and progress is the norm, since that is pretty much all we see!  This creates a deep feeling of discontent in people, which I believe is the root cause of much of the unhappiness people are experiencing today. 
Becoming consciously aware that what we see on social media is not the "full story" can be a good first step to remove that discontent✌🏽
